<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise label="mcqmulteigenrepeated">
  <title>Recognizing a Repeated Eigenvalue</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      The matrix 
      <m>
        A =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          3 \amp 1 \\
          0 \amp 3
        \end{bmatrix}
      </m>
      has which eigenvalues?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>A repeated eigenvalue <m>\lambda = 3</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The characteristic polynomial is 
          <m>(3-\lambda)^2</m>, so the eigenvalue <m>3</m> has multiplicity 2.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Eigenvalues <m>3</m> and <m>1</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the diagonal entries do not directly give distinct eigenvalues in this case.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Eigenvalues <m>1</m> and <m>3</m> with multiplicity one each.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the eigenvalue is repeated, not distinct.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqmulteigendefective">
  <title>Determining When a Matrix Is Defective</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      A matrix with a repeated eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m> is called 
      <em>defective</em> when:
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>It has fewer independent eigenvectors than the multiplicity of <m>\lambda</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. A repeated eigenvalue requires enough eigenvectors; 
          if only one exists, the matrix is defective.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Its characteristic polynomial cannot be factored.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No. This has nothing to do with being defective.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Its trace is zero.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No. The trace does not determine diagonalizability.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqmulteigengeneralized">
  <title>Purpose of a Generalized Eigenvector</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      If a matrix has only one eigenvector <m>\vec{v}</m> for a repeated eigenvalue,
      why do we introduce a generalized eigenvector <m>\vec{w}</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>To construct a second independent solution of the form <m>(t\vec{v} + \vec{w}) e^{\lambda t}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. A generalized eigenvector provides the missing second solution 
          when only one eigenvector exists.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>To find a new eigenvalue.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—generalized eigenvectors do not create new eigenvalues.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>To force the matrix to become diagonalizable.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. A defective matrix cannot be made diagonalizable by choosing more vectors.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqmulteigenequation">
  <title>Equation for Finding a Generalized Eigenvector</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>\vec{v}</m> is an eigenvector for a repeated eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m>, 
      which equation must a generalized eigenvector <m>\vec{w}</m> satisfy?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>(A - \lambda I)\vec{w} = \vec{v}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. This equation produces a vector <m>\vec{w}</m> that generates 
          the second independent solution.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>A\vec{w} = \lambda\vec{w}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that would make <m>\vec{w}</m> another eigenvector, which does not exist.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>(A - \lambda I)^2 \vec{w} = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>
        Not the defining equation—the generalized eigenvector is found using 
        <m>(A-\lambda I)\vec{w} = \vec{v}</m>.
      </p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqmulteigensolutionform">
  <title>Structure of the General Solution for a Defective Matrix</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      If a matrix has a repeated eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m> with only one eigenvector
      <m>\vec{v}</m> and a generalized eigenvector <m>\vec{w}</m>, what does the
      general solution to <m>\vec{x}' = A\vec{x}</m> look like?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\vec{x}(t) = C_1 \vec{v} e^{\lambda t} + C_2 (\vec{v} t + \vec{w}) e^{\lambda t}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. This is the full solution when only one 
          eigenvector exists.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\vec{x}(t) = C_1 \vec{v} e^{\lambda t} + C_2 \vec{w} e^{\lambda t}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this does not produce two independent solutions.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\vec{x}(t) = (C_1 + C_2)t\, e^{\lambda t}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—solutions must be vector‑valued and use <m>\vec{v}</m> and <m>\vec{w}</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

  <!-- PROBLEM 1 -->
  <exercise xml:id="multeigennew1">
    <title>Checking Whether a Matrix Is Defective</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the matrix  
        <m>
          A =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            4 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 4
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </m>
      </p>
        <ol> 
          <li> 
            <p> Compute the eigenvalue(s) of <m>A</m>.  
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
              <p>Find all eigenvectors of <m>A</m> and determine whether the matrix
        is defective.
            </p>
          </li> 
        </ol>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <strong>(a)</strong>  
        The characteristic polynomial is  
        <m>\det(A - \lambda I) = (4-\lambda)^2</m>,  
        so the only eigenvalue is the repeated eigenvalue  
        <m>\lambda = 4</m>.  
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>(b)</strong>  
        To find the eigenvectors, solve  
        <m>(A - 4I)\vec{v} = 0</m>.  
        That matrix is  
      </p>

      <me>
        A - 4I =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          0 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 0
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        The equation <m>2v_2 = 0</m> implies <m>v_2 = 0</m>, while <m>v_1</m> is
        free.  
        Thus every eigenvector has the form  
      </p>

      <me>
        \vec{v} =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \\
          0
        \end{bmatrix} c.
      </me>

      <p>
        There is only <em>one</em> linearly independent eigenvector, even
        though the eigenvalue has algebraic multiplicity 2.  
        Hence <m>A</m> is <em>defective</em>.   
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>



  <!-- PROBLEM 2 -->
  <exercise xml:id="multeigennew2">
    <title>Finding a Generalized Eigenvector</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Let  
        <m>
          A =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            5 \amp 1 \\
            0 \amp 5
          \end{bmatrix},
        </m>
        which has a repeated eigenvalue <m>\lambda = 5</m>.  
        The unique eigenvector (up to scaling) is  
        <m>\vec{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>.  
      </p>
      <p>
        Find a generalized eigenvector <m>\vec{w}</m> satisfying  
        <m>(A - 5I)\vec{w} = \vec{v}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Compute  
      </p>

      <me>
        A - 5I =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          0 \amp 1 \\
          0 \amp 0
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        We seek <m>\vec{w} = \begin{bmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \end{bmatrix}</m> such that  
      </p>

      <me>
        (A - 5I)\vec{w}
        =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          w_2 \\
          0
        \end{bmatrix}
        =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \\
          0
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Thus <m>w_2 = 1</m>, and <m>w_1</m> is arbitrary.  
        The simplest choice is  
      </p>

      <me>
        \vec{w} =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          0 \\
          1
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        This exactly matches the definition of a generalized eigenvector: solve <m>(A - \lambda I)\vec{w} = \vec{v}</m>.  
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>



  <!-- PROBLEM 3 -->
  <exercise xml:id="multeigennew3">
    <title>Constructing the Full Solution for a Defective Matrix</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        For the matrix  
        <m>
          A =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 1 \\
            0 \amp 2
          \end{bmatrix},
        </m>
        the eigenvalue is <m>\lambda = 2</m> with eigenvector  
        <m>\vec{v} = \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 0\end{bmatrix}</m>.  
        A generalized eigenvector is  
        <m>\vec{w} = \begin{bmatrix}0 \\ 1\end{bmatrix}</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Write the general solution to <m>\vec{x}' = A\vec{x}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        A defective matrix with one eigenvector and one
        generalized eigenvector yields solutions  
      </p>

      <me>
        \vec{x}_1(t) = \vec{v} e^{2t},
        \vec{x}_2(t) = (\vec{v} t + \vec{w}) e^{2t}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Therefore the general solution is  
      </p>

      <me>
        \vec{x}(t)
        =
        C_1
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \\ 0
        \end{bmatrix}
        e^{2t}
        +
        C_2
        \left(
          t
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \\ 0
          \end{bmatrix}
          +
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \\ 1
          \end{bmatrix}
        \right)
        e^{2t}.
      </me>

      <p>
        This is the standard repeated‑eigenvalue solution for a defective system.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

